Mixing models require a TDF to adequately account for changes in uptake of carbon and nitrogen through the food chain. TDFs can vary significantly and therefore mixing models require a TDF to be specific for each tissue type , species, and isotope (e.g., ∆13C and ∆15N). TDFs for a particular species may be obtained from the literature, but ideally are experimentally determined with controlled captive feeding trials. Approximated TDFs produced from averages across multiple taxa can be used if species-specific TDFs are not available in the literature: 0.4‰ for ∆13C and 3.4‰ for ∆15N ( Post, 2002 ). The use of non-species-specific TDFs will increase uncertainty in the estimation of consumer diet using mixing models (
Caut et al. , 2009
), and therefore researchers have been urged to use experimentally derived TDFs for mixing models (e.g.,
Caut et al. , 2009
; Martínez del
Rio et al. , 2009
; Stock & Semmens, 2016 );
Wolf et al. , 2009
).

To obtain diet information of a consumer by stable isotope analysis, a tissue sample is required from the consumer and from each of the potential diet sources. Muscle tissue is commonly used for analysis because muscle generally reflects the long-term isotope signature and thus reflects longer term diet of the animal and is less prone to short-term changes in diet ( Fry, 2006 ), unlike, for example, hair or shell tissue. In many cases, the required tissue involves lethal sampling of the individual (
Carolan et al. , 2012
). Non-lethal sampling options for crustaceans, such as carapace, leg, antenna, and faeces samples, however, have been proven to be promising alternatives to muscle tissue, due to high isotopic correlations between tissues in some species (
Carolan et al. , 2012
;
Day et al. , 2022
;
Mazumder et al. , 2018
). Non-lethal sampling provides a useful alternative in situations investigating protected populations or long-term, repetitive-sampling experiments. Removing a single leg rather than a more invasive or whole-animal sample, it provides the opportunity to sample industry caught crustaceans destined for market without compromising sale value, which could allow for large sample sizes.

Stable isotope measurements reflect a long-term temporal scale for dietary uptake. But as tissue is constantly being replaced, and because diet may seasonally change in the wild, the exact stable-isotope turnover rate for a given tissue remains unknown ( Suring & Wing, 2009 ;
Carolan et al. , 2012
;
Madigan et al. , 2021
). The present work aims to contribute to filling this knowledge gap by determining isotope fractionation and variability in
J. edwardsii
.

Carbon and nitrogen stable isotopes were analysed consecutively for each sample using flash combustion isotope ratio mass spectrometry (varioPYRO cube coupled to Isoprime100 mass spectrometer; Elementar, Langenselbold, 
Germany
). The nitrogen produced during combustion was directly fed into the mass spectrometer and measured against a reference gas. Carbon dioxide was trapped in the meantime and released into the mass spectrometer after the nitrogen isotope measurement was completed and the system retuned accordingly. Stable isotope abundances are reported in delta (
δ
) values as the deviations from conventional standards in parts per mil (‰) from equation 1:

We found a significant increase in δ 15 N across all treatments in both muscle tissue and in the exoskeleton at 18 mo. We are uncertain whether this could be due to the lobster’s life stage, or influence of upstream terrestrial and/or marine farming on the nitrogen in the untreated tank water. Data on salinity from the water source suggests a significant flood event may have occurred in the 4-mo preceding our 18-mo sampling event (Supplementary material Fig. S1 ). A flood of fresh water, enriched with land-based fertilisers, could provide reason for higher nutrient loading in the tank water, but we did not see similar enrichment in δ 15 N in the samples after a different potential flood event earlier in the experiments, so this conclusion is uncertain. Due to timing and resources, we were unable to run the experiment for longer, but trials like this with different life stages of consumer and which run for longer time periods with regular water nutrient monitoring would be worth further investigation. This rapid change in δ 15 N further highlights the importance of sampling sources at the same time as consumers to avoid temporal mismatch in unexpected changing conditions. Our diet species (fish and mussels) are also a potential source of isotopic variation due to external sourcing of the product, which could be improved on in future experiments by ensuring homogeneity of the sources. Further, the δ 13 C signature of our sea urchin source was highly variable between individuals and so could be reason for unexpected variation in the consumer. In other studies of the same sea urchin species (
C. rodgersii
), such a strong variation was not seen (JS, unpublished data), implying this variation requires more research as to whether this could be large individual spread/variation or a sampling error. More investigation into the mechanisms behind short-term stable isotope variability in lobsters and variability of signature between individuals of the same species (e.g.,
C. rodgersii
) would improve the reliability of stable isotope methods for dietary analysis.
